properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Temperatures dropping to -40 degrees tonight will bring extreme wind chill values near -50 to Tuktoyaktuk and Aklavik this evening and overnight. These wind chill values are expected to moderate Saturday morning. ### Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NTStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A prolonged period of very cold wind chills is expected. A cold arctic ridge of high pressure will remain entrenched over central and northern Yukon this weekend. With temperatures near minus 45 during the overnight and morning hours wind chills of minus 50 will occur with a very slight breeze. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls are expected. Under the snow squall bands, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to the heavy snow combined with blowing snow, and snow will quickly accumulate. Snowsqualls will affect the coast this afternoon. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Snow squall warnings are issued when bands of snow form that produce intense accumulating snow or near zero visibilities. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Weather Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Winter Weather Travel Advisory in effect for today. Snow, enhanced by Lake Superior, is expected to continue today into this evening. Strong southwesterly wind gusts of 50 to 70 km/h will also result in blowing snow over exposed areas. Total snowfall amounts of 10 to 15 cm are possible by the time the snow weakens later this evening or overnight. Travel is expected to be hazardous today due to heavy snow and blowing snow resulting in reduced visibilities. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
